oyed by the regimes to win over the masses for their cause. Among these, fascist propaganda has traditionally been seen as the key means of influencing public opinion. Only recently has the "fascination with Fascism" become a topic of enquiry that has also formed the guiding interest of this volume: it offers, for the first time, a comparative analysis of the forms and functions of theater in countries governed by fascist or para-fascist regimes. By examining a wide spectrum of theatrical manifestations in a number of States with a varying degree of fascistization, these studies establish some of the similarities and differences between the theatrical cultures of several cultures in the interwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aFascism and theaterzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascism and theaterzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism and theater. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh1 aAdded, Serge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerghaus, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerghaus, Günter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCavallo, Pietro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Emilio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKühnl, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinares, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLondon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanse, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato